text: Looks fun to me. About on par with Guardians of the Galaxy anyway. As a reader, I'm actually more familiar with Valerian & Laureline than I am with Guardians of the Galaxy. At least they have a proven lead actor with this one (Kill Your Darlings), instead of a comedian from a sitcom like Guardians did (Parks & Recreation), so there's less to be worried about already. I don't see Ms. Delevigne's track record as an actress as any better or worse than Zoe Saldana, so her presence in this film doesn't bother me at all (just as the mostly-meh Ms. Saldana's presence didn't bother me in Guardians or any of the Star Trek films). And Luc Besson is a far and away more talented director than James Gunn could ever hope to be; plus he's not shackled to Marvel Studios asshole producers, and thus the potential for a more creative film is quite high here. Guardians of the Galaxy was a good movie, but I have higher hopes for new blood, whatever form it may take.

text: 170 million euros, huh? risky business, let me tell you that. i mean, i'm not saying what kind of movie this will be: it might suck balls, it might be awesome or just plain average (most likely the latter) but it's gonna have a hell of a hard time making any profit. that's about $180 million we're talking about and new sci-fi franchises have been faring so poorly in the recent years.  add to that no actual star in the cast and the source material being strange to at least 95% of the audiences (i'm from Poland and Franco-Belgian comic books have always been damn pretty popular around here but even then, i just never heard about this one). sorry to say but i just can't see this Valerian thing making anywhere beyond $100m, regardless of critical reception. i'll be really surprised to be proven wrong, it just seems to have that John Carter-y flop aura pasted all over it

text: As a major fan of the comic book series since the 70s (the best sci-fi comic book of all time imo), I am incredibly pleased with this trailer. I recognize complete scenes from the "The Ambassador Of The Shadows" (the comic book the movie is based on), I recognize the aliens, the tone of the comic, and a lot more. And this makes me confident that Luc Besson have been faithful to the story and the visuals and the tone, while, of course, amped it all up for a movie adaptation of today. I very much look forward to seeing my favorite sci-fi heroes finally make it to the movie screen, and can't wait until July 2017!!!

text: Valerian is the 1967 french comic book that started it all. As Mezi√®re (one of the two creators of Valerian) said : " Before us, nobody had told story like this, everything was possible in the series, each new album could lead us absolutely anywhere we wanted to go." The seminal work of Mezi√®re and Christin and all of the french artists at Metal Hurlant (Heavy Metal magazine) was for a long time a major source of inspiration for a lot of movie directors, like Ridley Scott, George Miller, James Cameron and George Lucas. Starwars is a "tribute" (some people says "rip off") to Valerian, there are literally dozens of shots from all the episodes that came frome the strips of Valerian. The Millenium Falcon is a copy from the Valerian and Laureline spaceship, some of the alien races in starwars came from Valerian, and there are a lot of similitudes in the two universe ( the carbonite of han solo, the cantina, the clothes of the characters etc etc) . This is maybe not so bad because all these artists were sharing the same counter-culture at that time, but Mezi√®re was really upset about it and wrote some letters to Lucas after starwars was released.  This Valerian movie is not a rip off of anything like mass effects, starwars , Guardians of the Galaxy, Avatar or John Carter. It is made as a tribute to the comics that made space opera the way it is in many film and games today. Luc Besson (director) asked Mezi√®re if he had been credited for Star Wars and Mezi√®re answered no. This is one of the many reason why the Valerian movie exists today. Luc Besson and Jean-Claude Mezi√®re have already worked together on the Fifth Element, Mezi√®re was the art director of the movie with Moebius and Valerian is the most massive and expensive movie ever made in France.   Will it be a great movie regarding of the source material and the budget ? Sure we can't know until it has reached movie theaters.

text: Book to film story adaptations are a hit or miss. Statistically speaking, they're more often a miss than a hit, especially for science fiction/fantasy space stories. The song isn't bad on its own, but it was a poor choice for this trailer because the dissonant cadence is cringingly awkward to sit through (seriously, WTF?), particularly with the action scenes. What really drives the nail into this film's proverbial coffin is not only an obvious lack of chemistry between the characters (it'd take a moron not to notice), but the ridiculous amount of vibrant CGI clashes with the comparatively lusterless live action characters and props.   Something tells me that this movie is going to be about as awesome as "John Carter" and "Jupiter Rising" and by awesome, I mean terrible. This film is going to crash and burn harder than Taylor Lautner's post-Twilight career.

text: Coming from a French well known comic book (early 70's): Valerian, space time agent (Valerian agent spatio-temporel). Loved the comic, huge universe, a lot of depth, Star Wars kind of universe but more "organic", less "tech". A lot of similitude from these characters found Star Wars movies... yes, Star Wars was very inspired (to say the least) by this French comic. Typical French base too: slow bureaucrats controlling the world, greedy bankers, a bit of sex (Laureline is using her charms very often), smoking / heavy drinkers characters (Shingouz), ...    As Besson is French, no doubt he will adapt this movie in the proper way with fresh new faces (except Rhianna). As the comic is based on characters that look like young adults, expect the same from the movie.  If well done, it can be a huge franchise as there are a lot of books to take stories from. Once again, there is enough material from this comic to get something great and not just a one of.

text: When you read through the comments, it's funny how little nuance is recognized or expressed, at least with American movie goers. Their expectations always seem to be so... simplistic.  So many seem to have one or two things that either stand out for them as related to some other story/movie/experience or there's some singular production element that's going to be their one big "deal breaker". "If this movie has _any_ CGI, then it will 'suck'". "Actor/actress X is in this movie so it's going to 'suck'". "This movie trailer reminds me of ' _insert other movie/video game here_ ' which means it's going to 'suck'". "I don't like the look of character X in this movie trailer which means the movie is going to 'suck'". "I don't like sci-fi movies so this movie is going to 'suck'".  <-- herp derp I find such view points to be so short sighted and so often wrong. For me, the trailer visually piques my interest and, since I've enjoyed some of Besson's previous movies, I'll go see it. Who knows? Maybe it won't 'suck'. ;)

Not that there's anything wrong with that, but it lacks creativity.  The city-planet looks like coruscant.  The heroes look like a male/female star-lord.  The green planet with bio-luminescent plants looks like Pandora.  The scene at 1:16 looks like colonial vipers leaving the Battlestar Galactica.  Some of the aliens look like they are straight from Star Wars.  It looks like an interesting movie, but like I said, it lacks some original thought and creativity.

text: My grandfather gave me a Valerian graphic novel as a gift once, and it was the one comic that really stuck with me. The artstyle, theming and everything else was just such an interesting blend of old tropes mixed with some fascinating storytelling that just enthralled me. It felt a bit like Fifth Element, Star Wars, and Guardians of the Galaxy, but with a slightly less whimsical mood to it. I'm really excited for this, but I'm not hugely impressed by the casting right now - I'm not sure how Dale DeHaan will be in a role like that of a Valerian - he looks like a kid, but Valerian always reminded me of a stony-faced, die-hard action hero. Definitely looked more like Superman-era Christopher Reed to me...

text: Another good epic film from Luc Besson. I watched the film in 3D and I can tell you that this film is amazing. First of all before I go further with the review, you need to know that this film is based on comic book, which means is more suitable for youngsters. I'm 41 years old and I liked it. Why I liked it? Because of the stunning script, adventurous story, visual effects, thousands of alien characters and species, unpredictable scenes, the introduction of the film where it tells you how Alfa city was created, and finally the creativity of Luc Besson to show different dimension of the future. This film is not about dialog or super acting. You don't need that in this film, this is an adventurous film set in the future based on comic book. For me this film is better than Avatar which I think it was more like a fairy tale in space, while this one is a proper sci-fi movie. You must watch it in 3D.......Luc Besson never disappoints

What experience they had in tactics and combat they lacked in the appearance of any relationship experience. The sexual tension between the two was palpable, but the sincere meaningful emotions (e.g. love) were just not believable at all. The plot about the inhabitants of Mul and the government officials trying to cover up a major mistake I bought, but this unbelievable love story subplot just got in the way.
